{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584343"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:44:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:44:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14451"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14451","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14451"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.8,0.04,0.06,0.08,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7146"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57267"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7146"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14451"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42726"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4903"},{"type":"tags","id":"4905"},{"type":"tags","id":"4909"},{"type":"tags","id":"4910"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"6646"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17055"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17137"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57267"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cell types secretes lubricating fluid that reduces friction between the beating heart and the parietal pericardium?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mesothelial cells","Fibroblasts","Cardiomyocytes","Endothelial cells","Smooth muscle cells"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Emesothelial cells\u003C/strong\u003E. These cells line both the visceral and parietal layers of the serous pericardium. They secrete a small amount of serous fluid that acts as a lubricant, reducing friction between the beating heart and the parietal pericardium during the cardiac cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibroblasts\u003C/strong\u003E are primarily responsible for producing and maintaining extracellular matrix components, such as collagen and elastin, in connective tissues. They do not secrete lubricating fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiomyocytes\u003C/strong\u003E are the muscle cells of the heart. Their primary function is contraction, not fluid secretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndothelial cells\u003C/strong\u003E line blood vessels and are involved in vascular function, not the pericardial cavity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmooth muscle cells\u003C/strong\u003E are found in the walls of hollow organs and blood vessels. They are responsible for contraction but do not secrete lubricating fluid in the pericardium.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mesothelial cells lining the pericardium secrete serous fluid that lubricates the heart\u0027s movement within the pericardial sac.","The pericardium consists of two layers: the fibrous pericardium and the serous pericardium.","The serous pericardium is further divided into parietal and visceral layers, both lined with mesothelial cells."],"references":["Jaworska-Wilczynska M, Trzaskoma P, Szczepankiewicz AA, Hryniewiecki T. Pericardium: structure and function in health and disease. Folia Histochem Cytobiol. 2016;54(3):121-125. doi: 10.5603/FHC.a2016.0014. Epub 2016 Sep 21. PMID: 27654013.","Loring, S.H., Butler, J.P. Pleural Lubrication and Friction in the Chest. In: Wang, Q.J., Chung, YW. (eds). 2013. Encyclopedia of Tribology. Springer, Boston, MA. https://doi.org/10.1007/978-0-387-92897-5_1305","Ovalle, W. K., \u0026 Nahirney, P. C. Netter\u0027s Essential Histology: Netter\u0027s Essential Histology E-Book. 2020. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42726"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14451"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42726"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-25T18:12:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-25T18:12:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7146"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57267"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"40","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/40"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attrib